The given polynomial is \( P(z) = z^8 - z^7 + z^6 - z^5 + z^4 - z^3 + z^2 - z + 1 \). This polynomial can be rewritten using the formula for the sum of a geometric series. Notice that:
\[ P(z) = \frac{z^9 - 1}{z - 1} \]
for \( z \neq 1 \). The roots of the polynomial \( P(z) \) are the roots of the equation \( z^9 - 1 = 0 \) excluding the root \( z = 1 \). The roots of \( z^9 - 1 = 0 \) are the 9th roots of unity, which are given by:
\[ z = e^{2k\pi i / 9} \]
for \( k = 0, 1, 2, \ldots, 8 \). Excluding the root \( z = 1 \) (which corresponds to \( k = 0 \)), the roots of \( P(z) \) are:
\[ z = e^{2\pi i / 9}, e^{4\pi i / 9}, e^{6\pi i / 9}, e^{8\pi i / 9}, e^{10\pi i / 9}, e^{12\pi i / 9}, e^{14\pi i / 9}, e^{16\pi i / 9} \]
